AGI - In the 2005 Conclave "they tried to use me" not to elect Pope, Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger.> This is what Pope Francis reveals in the book-interview "El sucesor" > (The successor), in which he speaks of his memories with Benedict XVI. The volume, written with Spanish journalist Javier Martinez-Brocal>, will be released on Wednesday, April 3, today the Spanish daily Abc anticipates a chapter. "In that conclave - the news is known - they used me," Francis explains that if the cardinals swear not to mention what happens in a Conclave, the Popes can do it.
"It happened - he says - that I got forty votes on one hundred and fifteen in the Sistine Chapel. They were enough to stop Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger's candidacy, because, if they had continued to vote, he would not be able to reach the two-thirds necessary to be elected Pope." To the question if they could not choose the same Bergoglio, Francis clarifies: "This wasn't the idea of who's behind the votes. The maneuver consisted of putting my name, blocking the election of Ratzinger and then negotiating a different third candidate. They then told me they didn't want a 'foreign' Pope.
<div </div
&nbsp;
"It was a complete maneuver. The idea was to block the election of Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger. They were using me, but behind them they already thought of proposing another cardinal. They still couldn't agree on who, but they were already on the verge of saying a name." Bergoglio explains in detail: "The Conclave began on Monday 18 April 2005. The first vote took place in the afternoon. This operation took place in the second or third vote, Tuesday 19 morning. When I realized in the afternoon, I told a Latin American Cardinal, Colombian Dario Castrillon: 'Don't joke with my candidacy', 'cause now I say I won't accept, huh? Leave me here. And there Benedict was elected." And Francis also emphasizes: Ratzinger "was my candidate." "It was the only one who could be Pope at that time," he says.
"After the revolution of John Paul II, who had been a dynamic Pontiff, very active, resourceful, traveling... a Pope needed to maintain a healthy balance, a transition Pope." Bergoglio points out his satisfaction for the election of Benedict XVI, already expressed during his first press conference on the return flight from Rio de Janeiro: "That's true. If they'd picked someone like me, that's a lot of trouble, I couldn't have done anything. At that time it wouldn't have been possible. I left happy. Benedict XVI was a man who accompanied the new style.> And it wasn't easy for him, huh? He met a lot of resistance in the Vatican." But with that election the Holy Spirit reiterates Bergoglio said to the Church: "Here I command. There is no room for manoeuvres." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
